WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:11.400
It's May, 1864, and the Union has entered its fourth year of war against the Confederacy.

00:11.400 --> 00:15.680
President Abraham Lincoln has fired yet another general and is looking for an officer who

00:15.680 --> 00:18.000
will take the fight to the rebels.

00:18.000 --> 00:23.200
Enter Major General Ulysses S. Grant, the hero of Vicksburg, and the type of general Lincoln

00:23.200 --> 00:28.240
knows will change the direction of the war in favor of the United States of America.

00:28.240 --> 00:33.520
According to the rank of Lieutenant General, a rank only held in wartime by George Washington,

00:33.520 --> 00:38.960
Lincoln tasked Grant with the job of leading the Union troops against the Confederate Army.

00:38.960 --> 00:43.280
Grant wastes no time in forming a new aggressive strategy that will attack the Confederacy

00:43.280 --> 00:48.680
from five different directions and take him, the new commander of the Army of the Potomac,

00:48.680 --> 00:54.160
into the field to face General Lee and the Army of Northern Virginia.

00:54.160 --> 00:56.520
Howdy.

00:56.520 --> 01:01.840
I am Kyle Bondo, U.S. Navy veteran, resident of Fredericksburg, Virginia, an amateur Civil

01:01.840 --> 01:06.800
War history buff, inviting you to join me for my new podcast, War Yankee.

01:06.800 --> 01:10.880
Follow me as I explore the history of the American Civil War, beginning with Grant's

01:10.880 --> 01:14.720
Overland Campaign of May to June 1864.

01:14.720 --> 01:16.880
Why am I starting in the middle of the war?

01:16.880 --> 01:21.560
Because I live in Fredericksburg, Virginia, where the 40-plus days of fighting started

01:21.560 --> 01:25.880
only a few miles away from my house at the Battle of the Wilderness, and then tore through

01:25.880 --> 01:31.100
my backyard into a Spotsylvania courthouse before concluding 80-some miles away to the

01:31.100 --> 01:32.960
South in Petersburg, Virginia.

01:32.960 --> 01:38.120
To make this podcast, I actually walked the path of destruction from Colpepper to Petersburg,

01:38.120 --> 01:42.240
Virginia, and stood where General Grant and the brave soldiers of the Army of the Potomac

01:42.240 --> 01:45.000
stood 156 years ago.

01:45.000 --> 01:50.520
I now truly understand what it took the Union Army, in both courage and sacrifice, to end

01:50.520 --> 01:55.280
slavery once and for all, and ultimately reunite the United States of America for a common

01:55.280 --> 01:56.280
good.

01:56.280 --> 02:05.200
War Yankee Overland is my American Civil War History Podcast, created by me, Kyle Bondo,

02:05.200 --> 02:06.200
and produced by Gagalpod.

02:06.200 --> 02:11.640
I hope you can join me as I follow the history hiding in my own backyard.

02:11.640 --> 02:13.200
Find out more at waryankee.com.

